WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.244
Respiratory syncytial virus, or RSV
bronchiolitis,

2
00:00:03.585 --> 00:00:06.985
is one of the most common causes of lower
respiratory distress in infants.

3
00:00:07.364 --> 00:00:10.944
And as a respiratory therapist, your
ability to recognize severity

4
00:00:10.944 --> 00:00:12.404
early is critical.

5
00:00:12.765 --> 00:00:15.944
In this lesson, we're focusing on how RSV
affects the

6
00:00:15.944 --> 00:00:18.165
small airways, what that looks like
clinically,

7
00:00:18.284 --> 00:00:21.284
and how to make real-time decisions at the
bedside.

8
00:00:21.924 --> 00:00:24.965
RSV primarily targets the bronchioles,
causing inflammation,

9
00:00:25.485 --> 00:00:27.024
edema, and increased mucus production.

10
00:00:27.625 --> 00:00:31.745
Because infants already have very small
airways, even slight swelling

11
00:00:31.745 --> 00:00:33.845
can significantly increase resistance.

12
00:00:34.564 --> 00:00:36.404
This leads to air trapping,
hyperinflation,

13
00:00:36.544 --> 00:00:37.845
and increased work of breathing.

14
00:00:38.625 --> 00:00:40.244
Think cause-right pointing arrow effect.

15
00:00:40.884 --> 00:00:43.645
Viral infection leads to airway swelling
and mucus plugging, which

16
00:00:43.645 --> 00:00:45.865
leads to obstruction, which leads to poor
ventilation,

17
00:00:46.125 --> 00:00:47.685
and increased respiratory effort.

18
00:00:48.645 --> 00:00:51.064
Clinically, these patients often present
with tachypnea,

19
00:00:51.705 --> 00:00:53.965
nasal flaring, retractions, and diffused
crackles

20
00:00:53.965 --> 00:00:54.505
or wheezing.

21
00:00:55.044 --> 00:00:58.965
One key difference from asthma is that
wheezing is not always the dominant finding.

22
00:00:59.805 --> 00:01:02.165
Crackles from mucus and airway collapse
are very common.

23
00:01:02.985 --> 00:01:07.004
From an RT perspective, your priority is
not just identifying

24
00:01:07.004 --> 00:01:07.485
RSV.

25
00:01:07.724 --> 00:01:10.025
It's determining how sick the patient is.

26
00:01:10.644 --> 00:01:13.025
Ask yourself, is the patient maintaining
oxygenation?

27
00:01:13.305 --> 00:01:14.745
Are they moving air effectively?

28
00:01:15.205 --> 00:01:16.165
Are they fatiguing?

29
00:01:17.144 --> 00:01:20.745
Diagnostics are often clinical, but pulse
oximetry is essential.

30
00:01:21.464 --> 00:01:24.264
ABGs are not routine unless the patient is
worsening.

31
00:01:25.084 --> 00:01:27.305
A rising carbon dioxide, just like an
asthma,

32
00:01:27.544 --> 00:01:29.385
is a late and dangerous sign.

33
00:01:30.485 --> 00:01:31.565
Management is mostly supportive.

34
00:01:32.565 --> 00:01:34.324
Oxygen therapy is the first line
intervention.

35
00:01:35.125 --> 00:01:36.144
Nasal suctioning is critical.

36
00:01:36.745 --> 00:01:40.525
This is one of the few conditions where
secretion removal can dramatically improve ventilation.

37
00:01:41.485 --> 00:01:44.925
High flow nasal cannula may be used to
reduce work of breathing and improve

38
00:01:44.925 --> 00:01:45.684
oxygenation.

39
00:01:46.544 --> 00:01:49.904
Unlike asthma, bronchodilators and
steroids are not routinely effective.

40
00:01:50.264 --> 00:01:53.605
So treatment decisions should be based on
patient response, not

41
00:01:53.605 --> 00:01:54.025
habit.

42
00:01:54.885 --> 00:01:57.025
Red flags include apnea, poor feeding,

43
00:01:57.544 --> 00:02:00.684
lethargy, worsening retractions, and
declining oxygen

44
00:02:00.684 --> 00:02:02.285
saturation despite support.

45
00:02:02.485 --> 00:02:06.364
These patients may require escalation to
CPAP or mechanical ventilation.

46
00:02:07.285 --> 00:02:09.005
Here's your board prep takeaway.

47
00:02:09.764 --> 00:02:12.345
RSV bronchiolitis is a supportive care
disease.

48
00:02:13.445 --> 00:02:15.324
Oxygen, suctioning, and monitoring are
your

49
00:02:15.324 --> 00:02:17.744
core interventions, not bronchodilators.

50
00:02:18.384 --> 00:02:21.845
And your RT clinical pearl, always
reassess work of breathing

51
00:02:21.845 --> 00:02:22.904
and mental status.

52
00:02:23.485 --> 00:02:26.304
A tired infant who looks quieter is not
improving.

53
00:02:26.725 --> 00:02:27.625
They may be failing.

54
00:02:28.285 --> 00:02:30.184
By the end of this lesson, you should be
able

55
00:02:30.184 --> 00:02:34.304
to connect the pathophysiology of RSV to
what you see at the bedside and

56
00:02:34.304 --> 00:02:36.684
make confident board-level clinical
decisions.

